            <article aria-labelledby="composting-heading">
                <h3 id="composting-heading">Composting for Healthy Soil</h3>
                <p>Composting transforms kitchen scraps and yard waste into nutrient-rich soil amendment. This practice reduces landfill waste while providing your plants with natural fertilizer.</p>
                
                <h4>Getting Started with Composting</h4>
                <ol>
                    <li>Choose a composting method that fits your space</li>
                    <li>Collect green materials (nitrogen-rich) and brown materials (carbon-rich)</li>
                    <li>Layer materials in proper ratios</li>
                    <li>Turn regularly and maintain proper moisture</li>
                    <li>Harvest finished compost after 3-6 months</li>
                </ol>
            </article>
            
            <article aria-labelledby="water-conservation-heading">
                <h3 id="water-conservation-heading">Water Conservation Techniques</h3>
                <p>Smart watering practices help conserve this precious resource while keeping your garden healthy. Learn about efficient irrigation methods and drought-resistant plant selection.</p>
                
                <h4>Water-Saving Strategies</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Install drip irrigation systems for targeted watering</li>
                    <li>Use mulch to retain soil moisture</li>
                    <li>Collect rainwater in barrels for later use</li>
                    <li>Choose native plants adapted to local rainfall</li>
                    <li>Water early morning or evening to reduce evaporation</li>
                </ul>
            </article>
            
            <article aria-labelledby="biodiversity-heading">
                <h3 id="biodiversity-heading">Supporting Local Wildlife</h3>
                <p>Create habitats that support birds, bees, butterflies, and other beneficial creatures. A biodiverse garden is more resilient and requires fewer external inputs.</p>
                
                <h4>Wildlife-Friendly Garden Features</h4>
                <dl>
                    <dt>Pollinator Plants</dt>
                    <dd>Native flowering plants that provide nectar and pollen for bees and butterflies</dd>
                    
                    <dt>Bird Habitat</dt>
                    <dd>Trees and shrubs that offer nesting sites and natural food sources</dd>
                    
                    <dt>Beneficial Insect Hotels</dt>
                    <dd>Structures that provide shelter for pest-controlling insects</dd>
                    
                    <dt>Water Features</dt>
                    <dd>Shallow dishes or small ponds that provide drinking water for wildlife</dd>
                </dl>
            </article>
        </section>
        
